    <div class="alpheios-lex-entry" lemma-id="n168" body-key="α">
          <b><span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἁδινός</span></b> : probably
            <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">thick</span>, esp. of things densely crowded and in motion.
          Hence ‘throbbing’ (<span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">κῆρ</span>), ‘swarming’
            (<span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">μέλισσαι</span>), ‘buzzing’ (<span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">μυι&lt;&gt;͂αι</span>), ‘flurried’ (<span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">μῆλα</span>), ‘sobbing’ (<span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">γόος</span>), ‘voiceful’ (<span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">Σειρῆνες</span>). Adv. with corresponding signification <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἁδινόν, ἁδινά, ἁδινώτερον</span>, ‘more dolefully,’
            <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἁδινῶς ἀνενείκατο</span>, ‘fetched a deep
          sigh,’ <i><span class="en">Il. 19.314</span></i>.</div> <div class="alpheios-lex-footnotes en"> </div>
    <div class="alpheios-lex-alph-source">From <u>
            <u>A Homeric Dictionary</u>
        </u> (Georg Autenrieth, New York, Harper and Brothers, 1891) </div>
